mixed  apnoeas  were tabulated separately. Percentage of periodic breathing was
also  determined.  Control  babies  and  SIDS  siblings  were compared on these
parameters, using the Mann-Whitney test. Between the 6th and 13th weeks of life
respiratory  pauses  were  significantly more frequent in SIDS siblings than in
control  subjects.  The  difference  disappeared after the 13th week. The roles
that  peripheral afferents and the circadian organization of respiratory pauses
play  in  determining the results are discussed. This technique does not appear
